  "prompt": "Is there a database of retail grocery prices?",
  "response": "Yes, there are various databases and sources that track retail grocery prices. Some notable ones include:\n\n1. **USDA Economic Research Service (ERS):** The USDA ERS provides data on food prices at both retail and wholesale levels, including detailed reports and charts.\n\n2. **Bureau of Labor Statistics (BLS):** The BLS publishes the Consumer Price Index (CPI), which includes data on the prices of grocery items and overall inflation rates.\n\n3. **Nielsen:** Nielsen collects detailed data on grocery prices and sales from various retail stores. Their reports often include insights into consumer purchasing behavior.\n\n4. **IRI:** IRI offers comprehensive market data and analytics for the retail grocery industry, including price tracking.\n\nIn addition to these databases, some grocery store chains also provide pricing information and trends through their own research and public releases.\n\nResearchers and consumers can access this data to analyze trends, inflation, and the impact of pricing changes on consumer behavior. Additionally, some specialized services may offer subscription-based access for deeper insights and more granular data.",
